<br>
&quot;To be honest there is so much content out there that the idea of a server wide list is kind of obsolete. There is rarely a time when a guild cant find something to do, granted that doesnt mean that you will always get what you want everytime.&quot;<br>
<br>
I understand the arguments that a raid schedule would become a way for some guilds to &quot;plot&quot; to steal the zone just before a guild that was scheduling time would get there, but to me, Myles has shown why it is pointless to undercut a schedule.  The fact is, there is so much content and so much out there to do, that even if a guild undercut another guild and &quot;stole&quot; their raid, it really wouldn't hurt that bad.  It would be fairly easy to go on to something else.  <br>
<br>
Maybe my topic is confusing some people in this respect:  I do NOT mean to try to start a Ragefire list of sorts.  Let's put  the Ragefire and other named spawn lists aside for a moment.  <br>
<br>
What I'm talking about is a schedule for raiding zones like Hate, Droga, or even the smaller ones like Unrest or Mistmoore.  It could be looked at as more an invitation for people to come out and maybe see what a guild is like if you group with them, or a chance to pick up a group in a little used zone.  <br>
<br>
Doesn't anyone else get tired of having to go to the same tired zones to get a group when you are below 50th level?  Let's face it, there is a cycle.  It usually runs like this:<br>
Loil<br>
FM<br>
OT<br>
DL<br>
So levels 20-50 are pretty much cut out for you.  Yes, you can group in other zones, but it's no where near as easy as the zones I just listed.  A list would be condusive to letting the below 50 characters get to do something besides pulling those goofy chickens and cats to the ledge in Overthere.  <br>
<br>
 <p>***  Givins, 47th level Erudite Wizard, Rodcet Nife  ***</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/ulhyra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lhyra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cons Threateningly </span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#333333>(8/4/02 11:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wishing for a server wide raid schedule</span><hr size=1> As you can see, personalities have a way of shining through....even on line.  Lots of jerks in the world, and we are not protected from them in our game.<br>
<br>
I'm afraid I have to agree with what has been said against a server wide list when raiding involves highly desirable loot outcome.  Greed is ugly.  <br>
<br>
Even without the list, it's ugly face is shown.  Although I have not participated in high end raiding, I read a lot.  There is backstabbing on a daily basis.   Duel guilded players sharing information about scheduled raids, etc.  Although there are other areas to raid if a spawn is taken, the prep time is difficult anyway, and adding a spawn change could break a scheduled raid.  <br>
<br>
I think the solution is to find a guild that fits your play style (*wink* Givins)<br>
<br>
Would anyone care to expand on the alliance?  Although I am not a member at this time, I love the concept.  From what I understand, this is a group of guilds scheduling raids together.  It's not perfect, but from what I've seen, working well.<br>
<br>
And in defense of the &quot;newbie&quot; comment. Givins is not a newbie.  He is an intelligent human being experiencing for himself new areas of the game as he levels.  I had the pleasure of grouping with him, and I felt comfortable.  For those that know this chicken @#%$, you know that doesn't come easy.<br>
<br>
