<br>
I've seen servers that use schedules, and rotations on various mobs.  And it normally starts out fine and good, assuming everyone agrees to abide by it.  But it always grows out of hand.  Example the Ragefire list.  You call it an entirely different thing, but really it's not, it's just done for a single spawn instead of a zone.  Sooner or later the capable guilds are going to get tired of waiting.  You can call it greed.  But it's not really a fair comment now is it?  <br>
<br>
Example, it took me two months roughly to get the final piece for my epic.  From Fear.  I had to spend each day seeing who was in the zone, finding out if the golem was up, if so when he went down.  Tracking times to know when I could go after him with a suffecient force from my guild.  I had to work for it and two months later I got it.  In RL I know a wizard from another server.  They play on rotations.  He's up in 6 months to get his epic.  When his guild is completely able to go in there just about any time and take it down.<br>
<br>
I don't agree with the fact that this game is about greed and rapid mobilization and competition.  But it's also why I chose not to play the high end game and stick with a small guild capable of challanging ourselves enough to have fun.  But this game is about work if you want to do anything from planes on up.<br>
<br>
There's also a reason most guilds don't normally take tag alongs on thier raids.  I know for CN, the only people non guilded with us are either applicants, or close friends to a member who can vouch for them.  It took us a good amount of time to get our abilities in synch and learn to work with each other.  When you add an unknown into the mix, you never know what you're gonna screw up.  I think that's as much as or more of a reason a schedule would never work then the relative few guilds that would actually use it for pre-empting. <p><img src=http://www.carpenocturnus.com/Brokenfang.gif>
