<br>
Some of the muck and insults that have been thrown back are puzzling.  Since when is an idea just an opportunity to call people names or talk about people's work habits?  Did I really say something to deserve that?  Do I know you?<br>
<br>
Some of the response has been enlightening.  For instance, I didn't know that Rodcet Nife once had tried this and it had failed.  I guess I am a &quot;newbie&quot; after all.  Or however you want to define a newbie.  <br>
<br>
Seems to me like a couple of you guys are &quot;newbies&quot; on civility and trying to discuss an idea constructively.  <br>
<br>
I really don't want to dwell on the flames.  If some of you people want to hijack my thread and turn it into a flame war, why don't you take it to the appropriate forum?<br>
<br>
In the meantime, I think that any idea of putting a schedule on a 50+ area is out of the question.  But the arguments that I hear do not seem like they would apply to the lower level dungeons.  (below 50)  <br>
<br>
By the way, let me end my post by saying thanks to the people that are writing constructive criticism.  Bring that on all you want, I don't mind being told I'm wrong.  <br>
 <p>***  Givins, 48th level Erudite Wizard, Rodcet Nife  ***</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/umylesofrodcet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Myles of  Rodcet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cons Threateningly </span><br>  Posts: 76<br> <font color=#333333>(8/6/02 7:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Raid schedule</span><hr size=1> Interesting, the people whom you are calling newbies on civility are for the most part the same people who are able to civilly settle disputes including conflicting raids and such.  Part of what makes me not want a list is the simple fact that most often any dispute can be settled by talking first.  You want an example:  Pre list Ragefire,  My guild Carpe Nocturnus butted heads with Brew Masters.  We both were ready to take over the Ragefire spawn and neither wanted to back down.  After a little bit of arguing we actually talked to each other and came to an agreement.  Now our 2 guilds feel like we can call on each other for help if needed, and have on occasion.  Keep in mind we came to this agreement over one of the most heavily fought after (non high end) mobs in the game.  Without the aid of any list or schedule.  And before anyone tries to say but the high end guilds wouldnt have worked things out with us.  We have also dealt with guilds like Ascent or the old Harbingers of Storms.  (in the case of Ascent I beleive it was a group of Ascent players not an &quot;official&quot; ascent raid)  It was never a matter of of having a schedule ro anything like that, it was more a matter of just talking like adults, and understanding that although I may not get what I want this time, the next time around I usually will.  Keeping that in mind, along with the fact that there is just so much out there to do I think having a server wide schedule is unneeded, and would in my mind only cause problems.  For instance last week on my guilds raid day we were scheduled to go to hate in search of the mage staff, when we logged on there was another guild there, so people scattered looking for a good spot to do, after discussing a few alternatives we ended up in ToV and had a nice fun raid.  Everyone there had a good time.<br>
<br>
All that being said, I can understand the appeal of being able to plan your RL around certain raids.  I know I dont get to do everything I want to do in EQ because RL takes precedence.  Our solution in our guild was just to pick certain times of the week when we would be raiding and then make the best of that time.  True we often times have to change plans at the last second, but we nearly always find something to do, and on the rare occasion that there was nothing that sounded appealing we would more than likely head right off to the arena. <p><FONT COLOR="green" FACE="forte" size="6point" >Myles Bonaduce</FONT> <P>

